Prologue
"Please!" pleaded Queen Eirwen. "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The Ice King looked down from his throne at his wife, his royal advisor beside him. She had given birth to a daughter. He scowled at the thought.
The little girl resembled her mother greatly: pale blue eyes, white hair streaked with blue strands. The Ice King thought that having a daughter would make him seem weak. After all, he had only sons until now.
"Your only options are to kill your child or to send her back into the wild. This is her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat her name as if it were poison. He always did that.
Frostwell had not always been one kingdom. It had been split into two, North and South. In the north, the non-magical realm. In the south, a kingdom filled with fantastic representations of power. Due to the greed of the North, the two realms had torn apart in an endless war until the South offered a truce.
The South was cornered, and its royal family would do anything to stop the bloodshed. They proposed that their only princess become the queen of the North and bear a son destined to be the future king. Then, the South would ally with the North to form a united kingdom. The North agreed, and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"I implore you, Your Highness, in exchange for my child's life, do whatever you want to me, imprison me, exile me, or even kill me," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child tightly in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at his wife, disgust in his eyes. Perhaps, perhaps he might pity her. The woman he had lived with for twenty-two years, who had always taken care of him during his darkest hours, who had given birth to his sons.
"Well, the child can live in the palace," he began, eliciting a sigh of relief from his wife. "However," he added, "you will be executed."
The advisor and Queen Eirwen herself shared a horrified glance. She lowered her gaze gently. "Yes, Your Highness," she said, bowing.
The Ice King ordered his royal advisor to take the child to one of Eirwen's vacant apartments. Once this was done, he commanded the guards to lead Eirwen to the execution site, where all the village inhabitants could witness the spectacle.
As the guards led her to the site, the villagers cried out in indignation at seeing their kindest queen about to be killed. Some people wept, others shouted and tried to attack the guards, while still others wondered what was happening, but all were outraged.
"Free her!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the most feared person in the kingdom made an entrance. The Fire User. Ex-Queen Eirwen would be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the cruelest punishment in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the gallows, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostfell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then, the fire user set the gallows ablaze, and a single tear rolled down the cheek of the ex-queen.
"Survive, Kari." This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the corridors
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds coming from the farthest room on the left side of the still frozen palace's south wing. Passersby who went past always wondered what was in that room, frightened by what might be inside. Servants' rumors danced through the corridors. It was believed that the late wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in this room, waiting for her release.
"They could not be more wrong," thought Ivory as she walked toward the south wing, while the servants went back and forth murmuring to each other. They have no idea what is in that room.
Of course, these rumors also applied to iel, as iel was the only person allowed to enter the room.
Toc Toc. "Miss Kari, are you there?"; whispered Ivory at the finely decorated door, covered in snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Iel wondered if she would invite her in, unlike the other times when iel had asked. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory giggled at the memory. Kari had thrown a book at her shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A single tap comes from inside, which seemed to mean she was there, but after all, where else could she be?
"Can I come in?" asked Ivory, remembering the time when iel had done so without asking permission.
A knock echoed from inside. It seemed to say yes. Ivory shivered, from the cold, but also because of the sound. It was strange for Ivory to hear noise coming from an allegedly empty room, even though she had been entering this room for years.
"Here I am," said Ivory, opening the door gently. The scene inside the room was unusual by normal standards, but not unexpected. There were papers everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and numerous ice statues were scattered around. The room had no windows and very little light. It was also colder than the rest of the palace (and that was saying something). A snowstorm seemed to have fallen inside.
The girl there was curled up on her bed, wrapped in her blanket, reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the space.
"Which notebook is it?" asked Ivory, sitting next to Kari on her bed.
